    "back": "A void title (e.g. from a fundamental mistake as to identity — Cundy v Lindsay [1878]) transfers nothing: no subsequent buyer can obtain title. A voidable title (e.g. from fraudulent misrepresentation) is valid until avoided: under s.23 SGA 1979, a buyer who obtains goods under a voidable title can pass good title to a bona fide purchaser for value without notice, provided the original owner has not avoided the contract before the resale.",
