    "front": "Distinguish the main forms of security over personal property: pledge, lien, and charge.",
    "back": "Pledge: the debtor delivers possession of goods to the creditor as security; the creditor has a special property in the goods and a power of sale on default (Re Hardwick [1886]). Lien: the right to retain possession of goods until a debt is paid — possessory liens arise by operation of law (common law or statute). Charge: a security interest that does not require transfer of possession or title — the chargor retains the property but grants the chargee a right over it; charges over company property must be registered (s.859A CA 2006) or be void against liquidators and creditors.",
    "details": "Fixed charge: attaches to specific identified property — the chargor cannot deal with it without consent. Floating charge: attaches to a class of present and future assets — the chargor can deal with the assets in the ordinary course of business until crystallisation (Re Yorkshire Woolcombers [1903]). On crystallisation, a floating charge becomes fixed and attaches to the assets then owned. Priority: fixed charges rank ahead of floating charges. Re Spectrum Plus [2005]: an account described as fixed charge was recharacterised as floating because the company could freely draw on it.",
