    "back": "Incoterms (International Commercial Terms, published by the ICC, latest edition 2020) are standardised trade terms that define the obligations, risks, and costs between buyer and seller in international sale contracts. They specify: when risk of loss/damage passes, who arranges and pays for transport, insurance, customs clearance, and delivery. Examples: EXW (Ex Works — buyer bears all risk from seller's premises), FOB (Free on Board — risk passes when goods are on the vessel), CIF (Cost, Insurance, Freight — seller arranges carriage and insurance to destination port, but risk passes on shipment).",
    "details": "Incoterms are incorporated by reference in the sale contract (e.g. 'CIF Shanghai Incoterms 2020'). They do not constitute a complete contract — they do not deal with transfer of property, price, or payment terms. 11 rules in Incoterms 2020, divided into rules for any mode of transport (EXW, FCA, CPT, CIP, DAP, DPU, DDP) and rules for sea/inland waterway only (FAS, FOB, CFR, CIF). CIF and FOB remain the most commonly used in commodity trading. Incoterms are not law — they are contractual terms that apply only if incorporated by the parties.",
