    "front": "What did Re Spectrum Plus Ltd [2005] decide about the characterisation of charges over book debts?",
    "back": "The House of Lords held that a charge over book debts described as 'fixed' was in reality a floating charge because the company was free to use the proceeds of collected debts in the ordinary course of business without the bank's consent. The label attached by the parties is not determinative — the court examines the substance of the arrangement, particularly the degree of control the chargee exercises over the charged assets.",
    "details": "The key indicator distinguishing fixed from floating charges is control: if the chargor can deal with the assets without the chargee's permission, the charge is floating regardless of its label. Agnew v Commissioner of Inland Revenue [2001] (PC): Lord Millett — a charge over uncollected book debts can be fixed, but once collected and paid into an account the chargor can freely draw on, the charge over the proceeds is floating. Re Yorkshire Woolcombers [1903]: Romer LJ's three characteristics of a floating charge — (1) class of assets present and future, (2) changing from time to time, (3) freedom to deal until crystallisation.",
